Author::::Jeremy Henderson
DateTime::::2016-03-08T18:33:47Z
Yes, what really made 84 onwards so creative was that the number of game-playing machines, most noticeably the c-64, reached a critical mass which meant that there was a much better chance of being able to make a return from game development, and creativity really flourished. There were certainly a lot of truly bad games that perished quickly, but so many completely original concepts were first developed then, and a great many of today's games are simply more sophisticated versions of these concepts, though not always more enjoyable!



Author::::Jeremy Henderson
DateTime::::2016-03-08T18:26:14Z
I suggest that you wait until you ARE older before declaring that change is harder the older you get. As an "old geezer" of 65, who was programming in COBOL 10 years before you were born, I can assure you that many of us don't have a problem with change. I've always been an early adopter, but as I got older I became a little wiser, and realised that blind acceptance was much less sensible than informed choices. Technology is littered with expensive failures which some people HAD to have the moment they came out. I doubt that you have much memory of the Commodore 64, which came out before you were born, and completely dominated the games market in the first half of the 1980s.



